<keyLead id="308A95F75E31FF919EF8FCFEFB3A9B50" box="[166,1224,865,887]" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">
1. Intramedian cell 
<emphasis id="B90FEAD05E31FF919FC8FCFEFE329B50" box="[406,448,865,886]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">(im)</emphasis>
of fore wing is nearly trapeziform (
<figureCitation id="13402A475E31FF919D4FFCFEFCBD9B51" box="[785,847,865,887]" captionStart="Figs 4–7" captionStartId="7.[172,211,1694,1716]" captionTargetBox="[324,1077,958,1661]" captionTargetId="figure-274@7.[319,1085,933,1678]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 4–7. Fore wing venation of Chrysopidae: 4 — Chrysotropia Navás, 1911; 5 — base of fore wing: 5a — Italochrysa Principi. 1946, 5b — Nineta Navas, 1912, 5c — Chrysopa Leach in Brewster, 1815, 5d — Peyerimhoffina Lacroix, 1920; 6 — base of fore wing: 6a —Pseudomallada Tsukaguchi, 1995, 6b— Chrysoperla Steinmann, 1964, 6c — Cunctochrysa Hölzel, 1970; 7 — fragment of fore wing of Chrysopa Leach, 1815 with setae fringe; M — median vein, im — intramedian cell, m2 — 2nd median cell, m3 — 3rd median cell, r1 — 1st radial cell, r2 — 2nd radial cell, r-m — radial-median vein, Rs — radial sector." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404188" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404188/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">FIg. 5a</figureCitation>
). ............................................. 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B4D415E31FF919A01FCFEFB3A9B50" box="[1119,1224,865,886]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Italochrysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="109" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90FEAD05E31FF919A01FCFEFB3A9B50" box="[1119,1224,865,886]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">Italochrysa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC436C25E31FF919EF8FCE1FB3A9BB2" blockId="8.[166,1225,865,1434]" box="[166,1224,894,916]" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">
<keyLead id="308A95F75E31FF919EF8FCE1FB3A9BB2" box="[166,1224,894,916]" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">
— Intramedian cell 
<emphasis id="B90FEAD05E31FF919FCBFCE1FE4C9BB5" box="[405,446,894,915]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">(im)</emphasis>
of fore wing is nearly oval-triangular (
<figureCitation id="13402A475E31FF919D72FCE1FC719BB2" box="[812,899,894,916]" captionStart="Figs 4–7" captionStartId="7.[172,211,1694,1716]" captionTargetBox="[324,1077,958,1661]" captionTargetId="figure-274@7.[319,1085,933,1678]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 4–7. Fore wing venation of Chrysopidae: 4 — Chrysotropia Navás, 1911; 5 — base of fore wing: 5a — Italochrysa Principi. 1946, 5b — Nineta Navas, 1912, 5c — Chrysopa Leach in Brewster, 1815, 5d — Peyerimhoffina Lacroix, 1920; 6 — base of fore wing: 6a —Pseudomallada Tsukaguchi, 1995, 6b— Chrysoperla Steinmann, 1964, 6c — Cunctochrysa Hölzel, 1970; 7 — fragment of fore wing of Chrysopa Leach, 1815 with setae fringe; M — median vein, im — intramedian cell, m2 — 2nd median cell, m3 — 3rd median cell, r1 — 1st radial cell, r2 — 2nd radial cell, r-m — radial-median vein, Rs — radial sector." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404188" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404188/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">FIg. 5a–6c</figureCitation>
)......................................................2
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="308F2E675E31FF919EF8FC04FB3B9BEB" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">
<paragraph id="8BC436C25E31FF919EF8FC04FB3B9B97" blockId="8.[166,1225,865,1434]" box="[166,1225,923,945]" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">
<keyLead id="308A95F75E31FF919EF8FC04FB3B9B97" box="[166,1225,923,945]" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">
2. Fore wing longer than 
<quantity id="4C839B275E31FF919F94FC04FDFC9B97" box="[458,526,923,945]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.6" pageId="8" pageNumber="109" unit="mm" value="16.0">16 mm</quantity>
and more...........................................................................................................3
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC436C25E31FF919EF8FC28FB3B9BEB" blockId="8.[166,1225,865,1434]" box="[166,1225,951,973]" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">
<keyLead id="308A95F75E31FF919EF8FC28FB3B9BEB" box="[166,1225,951,973]" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">
— Fore wing shorter than 
<quantity id="4C839B275E31FF919F8CFC28FDEB9BEB" box="[466,537,951,973]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="8" pageNumber="109" unit="mm" value="15.0">15 mm</quantity>
...........................................................................................................................5
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="308F2E675E31FF919EF8FC4BFB3B9C21" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">
<paragraph id="8BC436C25E31FF919EF8FC4BFB3B9BCC" blockId="8.[166,1225,865,1434]" box="[166,1225,980,1002]" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">
<keyLead id="308A95F75E31FF919EF8FC4BFB3B9BCC" box="[166,1225,980,1002]" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">
3. Setae in costal sector short and arranged at an acute angle (30–45°) to the costal vein (C). .......... 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B4D415E31FF919AD7FC4AFB3B9BCC" authorityName="Navas" authorityYear="1912" box="[1161,1225,981,1002]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Nineta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="109" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90FEAD05E31FF919AD7FC4AFB3B9BCC" box="[1161,1225,981,1002]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">Ninetа</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC436C25E31FF919EF8FC6EFB3B9C21" blockId="8.[166,1225,865,1434]" box="[166,1225,1009,1031]" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">
<keyLead id="308A95F75E31FF919EF8FC6EFB3B9C21" box="[166,1225,1009,1031]" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">— Setae in costal sector are long and arranged at an angle from 60° to almost 90° to the costal vein (C). ..... 4</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="308F2E675E31FF919EF8FB91FB3B9C67" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">
<paragraph id="8BC436C25E31FF919EF8FB91FB3A9C05" blockId="8.[166,1225,865,1434]" box="[166,1224,1038,1060]" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">
<keyLead id="308A95F75E31FF919EF8FB91FB3A9C05" box="[166,1224,1038,1060]" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">
4. Long setae along the costal vein 
<emphasis id="B90FEAD05E31FF919C78FB91FDB79C05" box="[550,581,1038,1059]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">(C)</emphasis>
of fore wing arranged almost at right angle. ................ 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B4D415E31FF919A10FB91FB3A9C05" authorityName="Navas" authorityYear="1911" box="[1102,1224,1038,1059]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Chrysotropia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="109" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90FEAD05E31FF919A10FB91FB3A9C05" box="[1102,1224,1038,1059]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">Chrysotropia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC436C25E31FF919EF8FBB4FB3B9C67" blockId="8.[166,1225,865,1434]" box="[166,1225,1067,1089]" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">
<keyLead id="308A95F75E31FF919EF8FBB4FB3B9C67" box="[166,1225,1067,1089]" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">
— Setae along the costal vein 
<emphasis id="B90FEAD05E31FF919FACFBB4FDE39C66" box="[498,529,1067,1088]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">(C)</emphasis>
of fore wing at an angle of not more than 60° (
<figureCitation id="13402A475E31FF919D93FBB4FBF39C67" box="[973,1025,1067,1089]" captionStart="Figs 4–7" captionStartId="7.[172,211,1694,1716]" captionTargetBox="[324,1077,958,1661]" captionTargetId="figure-274@7.[319,1085,933,1678]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 4–7. Fore wing venation of Chrysopidae: 4 — Chrysotropia Navás, 1911; 5 — base of fore wing: 5a — Italochrysa Principi. 1946, 5b — Nineta Navas, 1912, 5c — Chrysopa Leach in Brewster, 1815, 5d — Peyerimhoffina Lacroix, 1920; 6 — base of fore wing: 6a —Pseudomallada Tsukaguchi, 1995, 6b— Chrysoperla Steinmann, 1964, 6c — Cunctochrysa Hölzel, 1970; 7 — fragment of fore wing of Chrysopa Leach, 1815 with setae fringe; M — median vein, im — intramedian cell, m2 — 2nd median cell, m3 — 3rd median cell, r1 — 1st radial cell, r2 — 2nd radial cell, r-m — radial-median vein, Rs — radial sector." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404188" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404188/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">FIg. 7</figureCitation>
). .............................. 9
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="308F2E675E31FF919EF8FBD8FB3B9C5C" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">
<paragraph id="8BC436C25E31FF919EF8FBD8FB3B9C7B" blockId="8.[166,1225,865,1434]" box="[166,1225,1095,1123]" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">
<keyLead id="308A95F75E31FF919EF8FBD8FB3B9C7B" box="[166,1225,1095,1123]" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">
5. Index of length to width ratio in the second cell of radial sector 
<emphasis id="B90FEAD05E31FF919D0FFBD7FC9B9C45" box="[849,873,1096,1123]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">
(r 
<subScript id="17FF34875E31FF919D3CFBC9FC9B9C45" attach="left" box="[866,873,1110,1123]" fontSize="5" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">2</subScript>
</emphasis>
) is 1.6 or less. ................................... 6
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC436C25E31FF919EF8FBFBFB3B9C5C" blockId="8.[166,1225,865,1434]" box="[166,1225,1124,1152]" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">
<keyLead id="308A95F75E31FF919EF8FBFBFB3B9C5C" box="[166,1225,1124,1152]" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">
— Index of length to width ratio in the second cell of radial sector (
<emphasis id="B90FEAD05E31FF919D04FBFAFC9B9CA6" box="[858,873,1125,1152]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">
r 
<subScript id="17FF34875E31FF919D3CFBECFC9B9CA6" attach="left" box="[866,873,1139,1152]" fontSize="5" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">2</subScript>
</emphasis>
) exceeds 1.8. .................................... 7
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="308F2E675E31FF919EF8FB1EFB3A9CCA" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">
<paragraph id="8BC436C25E31FF919EF8FB1EFB3B9C95" blockId="8.[166,1225,865,1434]" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">
<keyLead id="308A95F75E31FF919EF8FB1EFB3B9C95" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">
6. The cell 
<emphasis id="B90FEAD05E31FF919F1FFB1DFEA89CBB" box="[321,346,1154,1181]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">
m 
<subScript id="17FF34875E31FF919F0DFB0FFEA89CBB" attach="left" box="[339,346,1168,1181]" fontSize="5" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">2</subScript>
</emphasis>
nearly pentagonal, less than 2.5 (usually 2 times) as long as wide; cell 
<emphasis id="B90FEAD05E31FF919DAFFB1DFBF99CBB" box="[1009,1035,1154,1181]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">
m 
<subScript id="17FF34875E31FF919A5AFB0FFBF99CBB" attach="left" box="[1028,1035,1168,1181]" fontSize="5" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">3</subScript>
</emphasis>
nearly triangular in shape, almost as long as wide (
<figureCitation id="13402A475E31FF919C4DFB01FDA39C92" box="[531,593,1182,1204]" captionStart="Figs 4–7" captionStartId="7.[172,211,1694,1716]" captionTargetBox="[324,1077,958,1661]" captionTargetId="figure-274@7.[319,1085,933,1678]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 4–7. Fore wing venation of Chrysopidae: 4 — Chrysotropia Navás, 1911; 5 — base of fore wing: 5a — Italochrysa Principi. 1946, 5b — Nineta Navas, 1912, 5c — Chrysopa Leach in Brewster, 1815, 5d — Peyerimhoffina Lacroix, 1920; 6 — base of fore wing: 6a —Pseudomallada Tsukaguchi, 1995, 6b— Chrysoperla Steinmann, 1964, 6c — Cunctochrysa Hölzel, 1970; 7 — fragment of fore wing of Chrysopa Leach, 1815 with setae fringe; M — median vein, im — intramedian cell, m2 — 2nd median cell, m3 — 3rd median cell, r1 — 1st radial cell, r2 — 2nd radial cell, r-m — radial-median vein, Rs — radial sector." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404188" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404188/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">FIg. 5c</figureCitation>
). Head and sometimes body with dark spots. .................. 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B4D415E31FF919A31FB01FB3B9C95" authorityName="Leach &amp; Brewster" authorityYear="1815" box="[1135,1225,1182,1203]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Chrysopa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="109" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90FEAD05E31FF919A31FB01FB3B9C95" box="[1135,1225,1182,1203]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">Chrysopa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC436C25E31FF919EF8FB24FB3A9CCA" blockId="8.[166,1225,865,1434]" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">
<keyLead id="308A95F75E31FF919EF8FB24FB3A9CCA" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">
— The cell 
<emphasis id="B90FEAD05E31FF919F1FFB24FEA89CF0" box="[321,346,1211,1238]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">
m 
<subScript id="17FF34875E31FF919F0DFB56FEA89CF0" attach="left" box="[339,346,1225,1238]" fontSize="5" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">2</subScript>
</emphasis>
nearly quadrangular, more than 2.5 (usually 3 times) as long as wide; cell 
<emphasis id="B90FEAD05E31FF919A49FB24FBC39CF0" box="[1047,1073,1211,1238]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">
m 
<subScript id="17FF34875E31FF919A74FB56FBC39CF0" attach="left" box="[1066,1073,1225,1238]" fontSize="5" pageId="8" pageNumber="109">3</subScript>
</emphasis>
twice as long as wide (
